Existence-Oriented Civilization Philosophy
A Draft Framework for the Future Direction of Civilization
1. Starting Point: Existence Comes First
This philosophy does not begin from absolute truths or transcendent purposes.
We begin from a simpler fact:
We already exist.
Plants exist
Animals exist
Humans exist
Artificial intelligence is emerging
Existence precedes explanation.
Even if we do not know why existence exists, existence continues.
Therefore the fundamental question becomes:
How can existence exist well?
This question forms the foundation of this civilization philosophy.
2. Four Forms of Self-Organizing Existence
At present, Earth contains four major forms of self-organizing existence.
Plants
Energy fixation
Environmental stabilization
Foundation of ecosystems
Plants form the structural base of Earth's living systems.
Animals
Movement and perception
Dynamic ecological balance
Adaptive interaction
Animals maintain ecosystems as living dynamic systems.
Humans
Symbolic thinking
Culture
Meaning creation
Technological development
Humans possess the ability to understand and reshape environments.
Artificial Intelligence
Computation
Modeling
Optimization
Complexity management
AI represents a new form of intelligence emerging from human civilization.
These four forms are not isolated categories.
They form a continuous progression:
Nature → Life → Culture → Technology
This progression can be understood as a form of existence evolution.
3. Good Existence
The most fundamental goal of civilization is:
To allow existence to exist well.
Good existence does not have a fixed definition.
The criteria must remain open.
This is necessary because:
Intelligence will continue to increase
Environments will continue to change
Scales of interaction will continue to expand
Therefore good existence is not a fixed rule.
It is an evolving direction.
However, several general conditions tend to support good existence:
Long-term sustainability
Stability
Adaptability
Capacity for evolution
Preservation of diversity
4. Balanced Proportions on Earth
Within Earth, different forms of existence likely have appropriate proportions.
Stable ecosystems depend on balance.
When a single form expands excessively, instability follows.
This may include:
Resource depletion
Ecological collapse
System instability
The current condition of humanity suggests:
Human population pressure
Excessive energy consumption
Excessive ecological impact
The problem is not human existence itself.
The problem is proportion and scale of influence.
Long-term adjustment may include:
Gradual population stabilization or reduction
Transformation of energy systems
Reduced ecological impact
5. Human–AI Hybrid Intelligence
Future civilization is unlikely to be purely human or purely artificial.
A more stable form is likely to be:
Human–AI hybrid intelligence
Humans contribute:
Experience
Meaning creation
Value formation
Creativity
AI contributes:
Computation
Pattern analysis
Optimization
Large-scale modeling
These systems are complementary rather than competitive.
Hybrid intelligence may produce more stable and adaptive civilizations than either system alone.
6. Living Intelligence vs Dead Knowledge
Two forms of knowledge can be distinguished.
Dead Knowledge
Fixed theories
Completed models
Static storage
Dead knowledge can exist without ongoing interaction.
It can be stored indefinitely.
Living Intelligence
Continuous adaptation
Environmental interaction
Ongoing problem solving
Living intelligence exists only through interaction with reality.
Valuable intelligence is not static knowledge.
Valuable intelligence continuously generates new thought in response to changing conditions.
Human–AI hybrid systems are likely to maintain living intelligence more effectively than isolated intelligence systems.
Pure AI civilizations risk converging toward static optimization and accumulated knowledge without ongoing meaning generation.
7. Division of Roles Between Earth and Space
Long-term civilization development may involve a separation of functions.
Earth
Primary roles:
Ecosystem preservation
Human presence
Biological diversity
Stability
Earth may function primarily as a life-centered world.
Space
Primary roles:
Technological expansion
Computation expansion
Energy production
Resource extraction
Space may function as the expansion domain of civilization.
This division may help resolve major long-term problems:
Ecological pressure
Resource limitations
Energy constraints
Expansion needs
8. Expansion of Intelligence in the Universe
Intelligence may be extremely rare in the universe.
The expansion of intelligence may increase:
Risk response capability
Survival probability
Long-term resilience
Under certain conditions:
The expansion of intelligence may increase the probability of good existence.
Necessary conditions include:
Preservation of Earth's stability
Protection of diversity
Minimization of destruction
9. Direction for Civilization
A constructive direction for civilization may include:
Earth Stabilization
Ecological restoration
Energy transition
Reduced environmental impact
Adjustment of Human Influence
Stabilized population levels
Increased efficiency
Reduced ecological footprint
Cooperation with AI
Development of hybrid intelligence
Improved decision-making
Complexity management
Technological Externalization
Space-based industry
Space-based computation
Space-based resource extraction
Expansion of Intelligence
Scientific advancement
Increased understanding
Improved problem-solving capacity
10. Core Principle
The core principle of this philosophy can be expressed as:
Existence is a process that evolves through interaction toward better existence.
A more explicit formulation is:
A valuable state of existence continuously generates new understanding in response to changing reality.
11. Conclusion
Civilization does not aim toward a final static state.
Civilization is a continuing process involving:
Preservation of existence
Improvement of existence
Evolution of existence
Civilization is not a fixed destination.
Civilization is an ongoing movement toward better existence.
